WEBVTT

00:02.503 --> 00:05.541
<i>[eerie music]</i>

00:05.631 --> 00:08.214
<i>(male narrator)
THERE IS A FIFTH DIMENSION</i>

00:08.300 --> 00:10.416
<i>BEYOND THAT
WHICH IS KNOWN TO MAN.</i>

00:10.511 --> 00:13.720
<i>IT IS A DIMENSION
AS VAST AS SPACE</i>

00:13.805 --> 00:16.183
<i>AND AS TIMELESS AS INFINITY.</i>

00:16.265 --> 00:20.305
<i>IT IS THE MIDDLE GROUND
BETWEEN LIGHT AND SHADOW</i>

00:20.354 --> 00:22.595
<i>BETWEEN SCIENCE
AND SUPERSTITION</i>

00:22.689 --> 00:26.227
<i>AND IT LIES BETWEEN THE PIT
OF MAN'S FEARS</i>

00:26.318 --> 00:28.980
<i>AND THE SUMMIT
OF HIS KNOWLEDGE.</i>

00:29.071 --> 00:31.654
<i>THIS IS THE DIMENSION
OF IMAGINATION</i>

00:31.698 --> 00:35.737
<i>IT I-S' A/VAREA VI/l-l/Cl-l
Vl/E CALL THE TVVILIGHT</i> ZONE.

00:41.124 --> 00:43.115
[explosion]

00:45.671 --> 00:47.662
[gunfire and bombs]

00:50.759 --> 00:52.500
[machine gun firing]

01:12.281 --> 01:14.238
KEEP THOSE TRUCKS COMING!

01:14.324 --> 01:15.735
CLOSE IT UP!

01:15.826 --> 01:18.739
I SAID CLOSE IT UP!

01:18.829 --> 01:24.495
<i>(male narrator) INFANTRY PLATOON, U.S.
ARMY, PHILIPPINE ISLANDS, 1945.</i>

01:24.585 --> 01:28.203
<i>THESE ARE THE FACES
OF THE YOUNG MEN WHO FIGHT.</i>

01:28.297 --> 01:32.006
<i>AS IF SOME OMNISCIENT PAINTER
HAD MIXED A TUBE OF OILS</i>

01:32.092 --> 01:35.005
<i>THAT WERE AT ONE TIME
EARTH-BROWN, DUST-GREY</i>

01:35.095 --> 01:40.010
<i>BLOOD-RED, BEARD-BLACK,
AND FEAR, YELLOW-WHITE.</i>

01:40.100 --> 01:42.216
<i>AND THESE MEN WERE THE MODELS.</i>

01:42.311 --> 01:45.178
<i>FOR THIS IS THE PROVINCE
OF COMBAT</i>

01:45.272 --> 01:48.560
<i>AND THESE
ARE THE FACES OF WAR.</i>

02:07.669 --> 02:10.411
EVENING, CAPTAIN.

02:10.505 --> 02:12.917
AIN'T IT A CRUMMY NIGHT?

02:13.008 --> 02:14.965
ROUGH?

02:15.052 --> 02:17.464
WE'VE GOT THE BRIDGE,
WHATEVER THEY WANT IT FOR.

02:17.554 --> 02:20.842
HERE YOU GO.

02:20.932 --> 02:24.926
JAPS HAVE GOT NAVAL GUNS STUCK IN
THE GROUND. THEY'RE ZEROED IN.

02:25.020 --> 02:27.102
THAT BRIDGE GETS IT
EVERY THREE MINUTES.

02:27.189 --> 02:28.975
<i>[explosion]</i>

02:29.066 --> 02:31.808
IF THE GENERAL WANTS TO KNOW
WHERE THE JAP FLEET IS

02:31.902 --> 02:33.518
IT'S DUG IN
ON THE ROAD TO MANILA.

02:33.612 --> 02:36.775
SERGEANT,

02:36.865 --> 02:38.367
WHO'D WE LOSE?

02:38.450 --> 02:40.191
LOTS OF WOUNDED.

02:40.285 --> 02:42.276
MAYBE TEN, TWELVE.

02:42.371 --> 02:48.617
F O U R D EA D .
<i>[suspense music]</i>

02:48.710 --> 02:52.123
HIBBARD, HORTON,
MORGAN AND LEVY.

02:52.214 --> 02:54.581
ALL RIGHT, SERGEANT,
BED THEM DOWN.

02:54.675 --> 02:56.507
CHECK WITH THE MESS.

02:56.593 --> 02:59.051
MAKE SURE THEY GOT
HOT COFFEE AND A MEAL.

02:59.137 --> 03:00.923
IF THEY'RE NOT HUNGRY,
EAT ANYWAY.

03:01.014 --> 03:02.630
YES, SIR.

03:02.724 --> 03:07.719
"A" COMPANY,
FIRST PLATOON, CHOW DOWN!

03:15.320 --> 03:16.822
FITZ,

03:16.905 --> 03:19.363
SIR?

03:19.449 --> 03:23.659
LOOK, I HAVE GOT ME A BOTTLE
OF PHILIPPINE TUPA IN MY TENT.

03:23.745 --> 03:26.157
NOW IT'S NOT EXACTLY
BOTTLED IN BOND

03:26.248 --> 03:30.082
BUT YOU'D BE SURPRISED WHAT
IT DOES TO A MAN'S OUTLOOK.

03:30.168 --> 03:31.329
COME ON.

03:35.465 --> 03:37.081
CHEERS.

03:37.175 --> 03:42.261
<i>[artillery
whistling overhead]</i>

03:42.347 --> 03:44.588
<i>[explosion]</i>

03:47.436 --> 03:49.518
BAD DAY, HUH, FITZ?

03:49.604 --> 03:52.187
A LOT OF WOUNDED,
FOUR DEAD.

03:52.274 --> 03:54.891
ALL IN TWO
AND A HALF HOURS.

03:54.985 --> 03:57.022
12 WOUNDED, FOUR DEAD.

03:57.112 --> 04:00.104
ANYTHING SPECIAL
ABOUT THE FOUR?

04:00.198 --> 04:02.986
ANYTHING SPECIAL?

04:03.076 --> 04:04.578
WHAT DO YOU MEAN?

04:04.661 --> 04:07.244
WELL, FITZ,
WE'VE LOST FOUR MEN BEFORE.

04:07.330 --> 04:09.458
WE'VE LOST EIGHT AND TEN.

04:09.541 --> 04:13.034
YOU SEEM TO BE TAKING THIS
A LITTLE HARDER THAN USUAL.

04:13.128 --> 04:16.416
I JUST WONDERED
IF THERE WAS SOMETHING

04:16.505 --> 04:17.916
SPECIAL.

04:18.007 --> 04:19.964
THESE FOUR MEN
WERE ALL UNDER 21.

04:20.051 --> 04:22.429
DOES IT HAVE TO BE
MORE SPECIAL THAN THAT?

04:22.512 --> 04:24.799
<i>NO, BUT THIS HAS
GOTTEN TO YOU, FITZ.</i>

04:24.890 --> 04:26.380
MORE THAN I'VE EVER SEEN.

04:26.475 --> 04:28.307
I'D JUST LIKE TO KNOW WHY.

04:28.393 --> 04:32.261
YOU'RE A PERCEPTIVE MAN, PHIL.

04:32.355 --> 04:35.564
IT'S THE MARK OF A GOOD
OFFICER, ISN'T IT?

04:35.650 --> 04:38.108
TO WARD OFF TROUBLE
BY ANTICIPATING.

04:38.195 --> 04:42.234
ARE YOU GONNA GIVE ME
A HARD TIME?

04:42.324 --> 04:44.065
I DON'T THINK SO, FITZ.

04:44.159 --> 04:45.741
YOU'RE A GOOD OFFICER.

04:45.827 --> 04:47.329
YOU GOT GUTS AND BRAINS.

04:47.412 --> 04:49.574
BUT SOMETHING
HAS GOTTEN TO YOU.

04:49.664 --> 04:52.326
I TOLD YOU,
I'D LIKE TO KNOW WHAT IT IS.

04:52.417 --> 04:54.875
WOULD YOU?

05:03.595 --> 05:06.087
HIBBARD, HORTON, MORGAN, LEVY.

05:06.181 --> 05:10.425
KILLED IN ACTION,
LUZON, P.I., 13 JANUARY 1945.

05:10.519 --> 05:11.634
SO?

05:11.728 --> 05:13.139
<i>SO YOU WANT TO KNOW</i>

05:13.230 --> 05:14.720
<i>WHAT'S GOTTEN INTO ME, PHIL,</i>

05:14.815 --> 05:18.149
I WROTE THOSE NAMES
DOWN YESTERDAY.

05:18.235 --> 05:21.273
I WROTE THEM DOWN
BEFORE WE WENT UP.

05:21.363 --> 05:25.448
WHY DID YOU WRITE DOWN
THE NAMES, FITZ?

05:25.534 --> 05:27.275
WELL, WE HAD A WEAPONS CHECK

05:27.369 --> 05:29.326
AND I LOOKED INTO THEIR FACES

05:29.412 --> 05:31.540
AND THOSE FOUR MEN

05:31.623 --> 05:33.739
<i>[artillery
whistling overhead]</i>

05:39.422 --> 05:41.584
<i>[explosion]</i>

05:49.766 --> 05:51.507
FEEL BETTER?

05:51.601 --> 05:55.811
I LOOKED INTO FORTY FOUR
FACES YESTERDAY MORNING

05:55.897 --> 06:00.357
AND WHEN I GOT TO THOSE FOUR,
THERE WAS SOMETHING SPECIAL

06:00.443 --> 06:01.729
A LIGHT OR SOMETHING.

06:01.820 --> 06:03.652
<i>I CAN'T DESCRIBE IT TO YOU.</i>

06:03.738 --> 06:05.570
<i>THERE ISN'T ANY DESCRIPTION.</i>

06:05.657 --> 06:07.739
<i>I LOOKED INTO THEIR
FACES AND I KNEW.</i>

06:07.826 --> 06:10.944
I KNEW THIS
WAS THEIR LAST DAY.

06:11.037 --> 06:13.153
I KNEW THEY WERE
GOING TO GET IT.

06:13.248 --> 06:14.659
I KNEW, AND THERE

06:14.749 --> 06:17.457
THERE WASN'T
ANY DOUBT ABOUT IT.

06:17.544 --> 06:20.286
WELL, THAT'S, UH,

06:20.380 --> 06:22.246
THAT'S FUNNY.
THAT'S REAL FUNNY.

06:25.468 --> 06:28.005
I HAVEN'T SLEPT MUCH.

06:28.096 --> 06:31.930
I KEEP WONDERING

06:32.017 --> 06:35.851
IS THIS THE WAY
IT'S GOING TO BE?

06:35.937 --> 06:38.599
IF EVERY TIME I STAND
IN FRONT OF A PLATOON

06:38.690 --> 06:41.273
AM I GOING TO BE ABLE
TO LOOK DOWN THE LINE

06:41.359 --> 06:43.896
AND KNOW WHICH ONES
AREN'T COMING BACK?

06:43.987 --> 06:46.445
FITZ, WHEN DID YOU WRITE
THESE NAMES DOWN?

06:46.531 --> 06:48.397
YOU'RE SURE IT WAS YESTERDAY?

06:48.491 --> 06:51.620
YOU'RE SURE IT WASN'T TODAY
ON THE WAY BACK IN THE TRUCK?

06:51.703 --> 06:53.444
YESTERDAY.

06:53.538 --> 06:55.529
YESTERDAY MORNING,
I SWEAR TO YOU.

06:55.624 --> 06:58.207
I WROTE THOSE
NAMES DOWN YESTERDAY.

07:07.928 --> 07:09.384
WELL?

07:09.471 --> 07:11.212
<i>(man)
I CAN'T TELL, CAPTAIN.</i>

07:11.306 --> 07:13.547
<i>THE STUFF YOU'VE GIVEN ME
IS INCONCLUSIVE.</i>

07:13.600 --> 07:16.092
I LOOKED UP HIS RECORDS.
HE'S NEVER BEEN WOUNDED.

07:16.186 --> 07:18.052
LOOKS LIKE A PRETTY
STEADY CUSTOMER,

07:18.146 --> 07:20.353
NO EVIDENCE OF BATTLE
FATIGUE OR ANYTHING.

07:20.440 --> 07:23.899
WHY HE SHOULD SUDDENLY GET
THIS WEIRD IDEA IS HARD TO SAY

07:23.985 --> 07:25.942
BUT WE BETTER RUN SOME CHECKS.

07:26.029 --> 07:28.441
HE BELIEVES IT.
YOU HEAR HIM TELL IT

07:28.531 --> 07:30.397
YOU ALMOST BELIEVE IT YOURSELF.

07:30.492 --> 07:32.824
<i>I'D APPRECIATE YOU
TAKING A LOOK AT HIM.</i>

07:32.911 --> 07:34.447
<i>HE'S A GOOD MAN.</i>

07:34.537 --> 07:38.496
HE'S ONE OF THE BEST
OFFICERS WE'VE GOT.

07:38.583 --> 07:40.324
I'LL DO WHAT I CAN, CAPTAIN.

07:40.418 --> 07:41.670
HE'S HERE NOW, YOU KNOW.

07:41.753 --> 07:43.539
NO, I DIDN'T KNOW.

07:43.630 --> 07:44.995
HE'S IN THE WARD VISITING

07:45.090 --> 07:46.797
ONE OF THE BOYS
FROM HIS PLATOON.

07:46.883 --> 07:50.968
I'M FINE, LIEUTENANT.
HOW'S THE REST OF THE BOYS?

07:51.054 --> 07:52.636
<i>OH, THEY'RE ALL FINE.</i>

07:52.722 --> 07:55.259
PORKY GOT A PIECE
OF SHRAPNEL ON HIS FINGER

07:55.350 --> 07:57.842
YOU KNOW PORKY, THAT'S ABOUT
AS BAD AS HE EVER GOT.

07:57.936 --> 08:01.304
[coughs]
HE'S A LUCKY KID.

08:01.398 --> 08:02.934
<i>THAT HE IS.</i>

08:03.024 --> 08:05.356
AND YOU'RE NOT
DOING TOO BAD.

08:05.443 --> 08:08.606
YOU GET THAT ALL PATCHED UP
AND YOU'LL BE GOING HOME.

08:08.697 --> 08:10.688
THAT'S NOT SO HARD
TO TAKE, IS IT?

08:10.782 --> 08:12.489
NO, SIR.

08:12.575 --> 08:14.486
IT SURE ISN'T.

08:18.289 --> 08:20.451
NO, NO.
THANK YOU, SIR.

08:20.542 --> 08:22.533
COULD YOU LAY IT
DOWN OVER THERE, LEASE?

08:22.627 --> 08:24.789
I WON'T BE NEEDING
IT FOR A WHILE.

08:24.879 --> 08:28.463
UH, LISTEN, SMITTY, I GOT SOME STUFF
TO DO SO I'LL SEE YOU TOMORROVV.

08:28.550 --> 08:30.461
YOU TAKE IT EASY,
YOU HEAR?

08:30.552 --> 08:32.212
YES, SIR.

08:32.303 --> 08:34.794
UH, ANYTHING YOU NEED--
YOU GOT STUFF TO READ?

08:34.889 --> 08:36.174
ALL I NEED.

08:36.265 --> 08:38.678
OKAY, YOU TAKE
CARE, SMITTY.

08:38.768 --> 08:41.351
THANKS FOR COMING, LIEUTENANT.

08:41.438 --> 08:43.554
<i>GOOD-BYE.</i>

08:43.648 --> 08:45.480
GOOD-BYE, SMITTY.

08:47.819 --> 08:49.526
<i>[suspense music]</i>

09:03.376 --> 09:05.663
YOU OKAY, LIEUTENANT?

09:05.754 --> 09:07.791
YEAH. I--

09:10.508 --> 09:12.044
YEAH, I'M OKAY.

09:33.531 --> 09:34.987
HE'S DEAD.

09:35.075 --> 09:36.406
JUST LIKE THAT.

09:36.493 --> 09:38.825
THEY GO AWFUL
QUICK SOMETIMES.

09:38.912 --> 09:40.698
AWFUL QUICK.

09:54.052 --> 09:57.386
FITZ?

09:57.472 --> 09:58.758
I WAS UP SEEING SMITTY.

09:58.848 --> 10:00.589
YEAH, I KNOW.
I READ HIS TAG.

10:00.683 --> 10:02.640
DOC SAID HE'S
GOING TO BE OKAY.

10:02.727 --> 10:03.933
NO, HE ISN'T.

10:04.020 --> 10:06.387
I TOOK A LOOK AT HIS FACE.

10:06.481 --> 10:11.021
I TOOK A LOOK AT HIS FACE,
AND I KNEW.

10:11.111 --> 10:13.227
AND A MINUTE LATER,
HE'S GONE.

10:13.321 --> 10:14.607
SAME THING?

10:14.697 --> 10:16.199
SAME THING.

10:16.282 --> 10:18.273
THE LOOK.

10:18.368 --> 10:22.828
THE FUNNY- THE FUNNY LIGHT
OR VVHATEVER IT IS.

10:22.914 --> 10:26.407
AND I KNEW,
AND I KNEW.

10:28.419 --> 10:30.126
FITZ, I CAN'T
EXPLAIN THIS, BUT--

10:30.213 --> 10:32.545
I DON'T WANT
YOU TO EXPLAIN IT.

10:32.632 --> 10:34.964
HOW CAN YOU EXPLAIN IT?

10:35.051 --> 10:38.134
HOW CAN ANYBODY
EXPLAIN IT?

10:38.221 --> 10:42.260
I JUST VVANT YOU TO BELIEVE IT, CAPTAIN.
THAT'S ALL I VVANT FROM YOU.

10:42.350 --> 10:44.341
I WANT YOU TO BELIEVE IT.

10:44.435 --> 10:48.019
<i>(Paramedic) BED FIVE, SIR.
SMITH. HE JUST DIED.</i>

10:48.106 --> 10:50.188
I'LL HAVE
A LOOK AT HIM.

10:50.275 --> 10:54.143
FOR WHAT?

10:54.237 --> 10:56.604
(Fitz) THERE'S NOTHING
TO LOOK AT BUT A BODY.

10:56.698 --> 10:58.029
HE'S DEAD.

10:58.116 --> 10:59.481
AND I KNEW
HE WAS GOING TO DIE

10:59.576 --> 11:01.158
'CAUSE I READ IT
ON HIS FACE.

11:01.244 --> 11:03.531
GO ON BACK, CORPORAL.
I'LL BE RIGHT IN.

11:03.621 --> 11:04.873
SO YOU KNEW,
LIEUTENANT?

11:04.956 --> 11:06.321
YOU BET I DID.

11:06.416 --> 11:08.248
I TABBED FOUR MEN
THE OTHER DAY.

11:08.334 --> 11:10.120
THAT'S ODD,
DON'T YOU THINK?

11:10.211 --> 11:12.794
<i>(Fitz) ODD? THAT'S
NOT 000, CAPTAIN.</i>

11:12.881 --> 11:14.713
<i>ODD WHEN IS YOU GO
3O DAYS ON THE LINE</i>

11:14.799 --> 11:16.005
AND YOU DON'T
LOSE A MAN.

11:16.092 --> 11:18.083
THAT'S ODD!

11:18.178 --> 11:21.136
ODD IS VVHEN YOU VVALK 25 MILES
AND YOU DON'T GET A BLISTER.

11:21.181 --> 11:23.138
NOW YOU'RE TALKING ODD!

11:23.224 --> 11:25.135
THIS ISN'T ODD, CAPTAIN.

11:25.185 --> 11:26.767
THIS IS NIGHTMARE.

11:26.853 --> 11:29.060
THIS IS A LOUSY,
DOG-FACED, LYING OFFICER

11:29.147 --> 11:31.013
<i>WHO CAN SEE DEATH
ON PEOPLE'S FACES.</i>

11:31.107 --> 11:33.394
<i>(Doctor) YOU'RE A
DOG-FACED, LYING OFFICER</i>

11:33.484 --> 11:35.612
WHO'S CRACKING UNDER THE STRAIN
FROM HAVING DONE TOO MUCH

11:35.695 --> 11:37.732
AND FELT TOO MUCH. FINALLY
HAVING TO SUCCUMB TO IT!

11:37.822 --> 11:39.608
I'M FIVE
FOR FIVE, CAPTAIN.

11:39.699 --> 11:41.861
HOW MANY COINCIDENCES
ADD UP TO A FACT?

11:41.951 --> 11:43.862
HOW MANY MEN
DO I HAVE TO TAB

11:43.953 --> 11:45.739
AS THE LEAST LIKELY
TO SUCCEED?

11:45.830 --> 11:48.117
HOW MANY MORE FACES
DO I HAVE TO LOOK INTO?!

11:48.208 --> 11:49.869
WHAT I WANT TO KNOW

11:49.959 --> 11:52.542
IS WHAT DOES IT TAKE
TO MAKE YOU GUYS REALIZE

11:52.629 --> 11:54.336
THAT SOMEWHERE
ALONG THE LINE

11:54.422 --> 11:57.210
I PICKED UP A TALENT
THEY DON'T TEACH AT O.C.S.

11:57.300 --> 11:58.756
ONE THING YOU MIGHT DO

11:58.843 --> 12:00.925
WHILE YOU'RE WAITING
AND SCRATCHING

12:01.012 --> 12:03.970
YOU MIGHT PUT TAPE OVER
MY EYES OR POKE THEM OUT

12:04.057 --> 12:07.766
OR DO SOMETHING VVHERE I
VVON'T BE ABLE TO SEE

12:07.852 --> 12:10.059
SO I VVON'T HAVE TO
LOOK AT ANY MORE FACES!

12:30.458 --> 12:33.291
NOVV VVE SPEARHEAD THE ATTACK
MOVING ACROSS AT THE POINT

12:33.378 --> 12:35.745
FOLLOWED BY BAKER
AND CHARLIE AND COMPANY.

12:35.838 --> 12:38.250
NOW, AT THIS POINT
TO THE EAST,

12:38.341 --> 12:41.834
SOME FILIPINO GUERRILLAS VVILL
BE CROSSING THE RIVER BY BOAT.

12:41.928 --> 12:44.545
<i>NOW THEIR JOB WILL BE TO KNOCK
OUT ANY AND ALL JAP GUNS</i>

12:44.639 --> 12:48.428
<i>IN THAT SIDE OF THE RIVER. SO THAT WE
SHOULD BE ABLE TO MOVE ACROSS THE BRIDGE</i>

12:48.518 --> 12:50.429
<i>AGAINST ONLY
SMALL ARMS FIRE.</i>

12:50.520 --> 12:55.435
VVE'VE GOT ABOUT 22 MINUTES
BEFORE VVE LOAD UP THE TRUCKS.

12:55.525 --> 12:57.983
GIVE YOUR PLATOONS
A GOOD BRIEFING.

12:58.069 --> 13:03.314
MAKE SURE THAT EACH MAN HAS A BELT,
FIVE GRENADES, SIX AMMO CLIPS,

13:03.408 --> 13:05.240
AND NO BACKPACKS.

13:05.285 --> 13:07.617
ALL RIGHT. THAT'S IT. GOOD LUCK.

13:15.920 --> 13:17.752
CAPTAIN,

13:17.839 --> 13:20.501
YOU STILL WANT MY PLATOON
TO TAKE THE POINT?

13:20.591 --> 13:22.628
I DON'T KNOW YET, FITZ.

13:22.719 --> 13:24.801
I THINK THAT PROBABLY--

13:24.887 --> 13:26.264
<i>[suspense music]</i>

13:28.599 --> 13:30.510
WHAT'S THE MATTER, FITZ?

13:36.691 --> 13:40.275
ARE YOU WELL ENOUGH
TO TAKE THE PLATOON?

13:40.361 --> 13:42.398
NOW, GUNTHER THINKS
YOU'D BE BETTER OFF

13:42.488 --> 13:45.105
VVITH THREE VVEEKS BACK AT DIVISION.
I AGREE VVITH HIM.

13:45.199 --> 13:47.907
THIS THING VVILL TAKE A FEVV
HOURS BUT IT VVILL BE MESSY.

13:47.994 --> 13:49.450
CAPTAIN, YOU BETTER NOT GO.

13:49.537 --> 13:51.119
WHY, FITZ?

13:53.791 --> 13:55.657
<i>[suspense music]</i>

13:55.752 --> 13:57.368
YEAH.

13:57.462 --> 13:59.044
IT'S ON YOUR FACE TOO.

13:59.130 --> 14:02.293
IF YOU GO,
YOU WON'T BE COMING BACK.

14:04.385 --> 14:05.921
FITZ, GET
YOUR PLATOONS SET.

14:06.012 --> 14:07.969
YOU'VE ONLY GOT
ABOUT 15 MINUTES LEFT.

14:08.056 --> 14:09.342
PLEASE--

14:09.432 --> 14:11.469
I'LL TELL YOU
WHAT WE'LL DO!

14:11.559 --> 14:14.551
VVE'LL TALK ABOUT IT VVHEN VVE GET BACK.
VVE'LL HAVE A DRINK TO IT.

14:14.645 --> 14:17.979
VVE'LL DRINK TO AN ILLUSION,
TO A COUPLE OF COINCIDENCES.

14:18.024 --> 14:20.391
NOW THAT'S IT, FITZ!
I'LL SEE YOU AT THE TRUCKS!

14:20.485 --> 14:23.318
CAPTAIN, YOU WON'T BE
DRINKING TO ANYTHING.

14:23.404 --> 14:25.782
'CAUSE YOU'RE
NOT COMING BACK!

15:03.986 --> 15:05.852
<i>[suspense music]</i>

15:11.494 --> 15:13.076
[walla]

15:18.042 --> 15:20.079
<i>[far away explosions]</i>

15:32.014 --> 15:33.345
LIEUTENANT?

15:33.433 --> 15:35.390
WHAT ABOUT IT?

15:35.476 --> 15:37.387
EVERYBODY SAYS
YOU CAN TELL.

15:37.478 --> 15:39.719
EVERYBODY SAYS YOU KNOW
WHO'S GOING TO GET IT

15:39.814 --> 15:41.646
AND WHO ISN'T.

15:41.732 --> 15:46.397
VVELL, HOVV ABOUT IT, LIEUTENANT?
GIVE US A BREAK, HUH?

15:46.487 --> 15:47.773
COME ON, LIEUTENANT.

15:47.864 --> 15:49.354
IT AIN'T FAIR--
YOU KNOWING!

15:49.449 --> 15:50.939
KNOCK IT OFF, FREEMAN.

15:51.033 --> 15:55.322
<i>(Captain)
ALL RIGHT, SERGEANT.</i>

15:55.413 --> 15:57.745
NOW LOOK, SOMEBODY
STARTED THIS WILD GAG

15:57.832 --> 15:59.789
AND SOMEBODY
WILL GET BURNED FOR IT.

15:59.876 --> 16:02.117
THERE'S NOBODY
IN THIS COMPANY

16:02.211 --> 16:04.498
WHO'S A MIND-READER.

16:04.589 --> 16:08.583
INCLUDING LIEUTENANT
FITZGERALD.

16:08.676 --> 16:10.587
<i>(Captain)
ALL RIGHT, LIEUTENANT?</i>

16:31.824 --> 16:33.201
YEAH. THAT'S RIGHT, SIR.

16:33.284 --> 16:35.366
ALL RIGHT,
SERGEANT, LET'S GO.

16:35.453 --> 16:37.615
YES, SIR.
LET'S GO!

16:37.705 --> 16:39.616
<i>(Sergeant)
OKAY, LOAD 'EM UP.</i>

16:39.707 --> 16:40.788
<i>LET'S GO!</i>

16:40.875 --> 16:42.616
<i>IN THE TRUCKS!</i>

16:42.710 --> 16:44.951
<i>IN THE TRUCKS, EVERYBODY!</i>

16:55.473 --> 16:57.134
[explosions]

17:23.041 --> 17:24.999
CLOSE IT UP!

17:25.086 --> 17:26.917
ALL RIGHT, CLOSE IT UP!

17:34.512 --> 17:36.924
OKAY, FIRST PLATOON,
FALL IN.

17:44.855 --> 17:47.938
FORGET ABOUT EXTRA DETAILS.
LET'S DO IT THE SAME.

17:48.025 --> 17:50.107
YES, SIR.

17:50.194 --> 17:52.401
COME ON,
HURRY IT UP.

17:52.488 --> 17:54.695
<i>FALL IN.
ROLL CALL.</i>

17:54.782 --> 17:56.022
<i>VERALL.</i>

17:56.117 --> 17:57.152
<i>(Verall)
HERE.</i>

17:57.243 --> 17:58.404
<i>ASHBAR.</i>

17:58.494 --> 17:59.700
<i>(Ashbar)
HERE.</i>

17:59.745 --> 18:01.736
<i>[roll cal! continues]</i>

18:34.405 --> 18:36.271
<i>(Commander)
FITZ.</i>

18:36.365 --> 18:39.107
JUST THOUGHT I'D DROP AROUND
AND CONGRATULATE YOU BOYS

18:39.201 --> 18:40.362
ON THE GOOD JOB YOU DID.

18:40.453 --> 18:41.693
THANK YOU, SIR.

18:41.787 --> 18:43.448
THE ODDS FELL
ON OUR SIDE.

18:43.539 --> 18:46.327
MUST BE ALL THOSE
RIGHT-HANDY JOB ON THOSE GUNS

18:46.417 --> 18:48.283
AND YOU FELLOWS
WALKED RIGHT ACROSS.

18:48.377 --> 18:49.412
RIGHT ACROSS.

18:49.503 --> 18:50.914
THAT'S FORTUNATE.

18:51.005 --> 18:52.712
THE AIR FORCE
MUST HAVE PICKED OFF

18:52.798 --> 18:54.539
AT LEAST SIX OR SEVEN
OF THOSE 25S.

18:54.634 --> 18:56.545
OF COURSE THOSE GUNS
WERE OPERATING.

18:56.636 --> 18:58.673
THAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN
THE LONGEST BRIDGE

18:58.763 --> 19:00.674
YOU'VE EVER BEEN ON,
OR THE SHORTEST.

19:00.765 --> 19:03.006
SNIPER FIRE,
THAT'S ALL YOU HAD?

19:03.100 --> 19:04.431
YES, SIR,
SNIPER FIRE.

19:04.518 --> 19:05.770
MM-HMM.

19:05.853 --> 19:08.185
WE LOST ONE MAN.

19:17.823 --> 19:20.440
OH, THAT'S A PITY.

19:20.534 --> 19:23.663
HE WAS A GOOD MAN.

19:23.746 --> 19:26.784
YOU WERE GOOD FRIENDS,
WEREN'T YOU, FITZGERALD?

19:36.801 --> 19:40.465
SO MUCH FOR MRS. RIKER'S
LOVELY WEDDING.

19:40.554 --> 19:43.421
SEVEN HAPPY YEARS.

19:43.516 --> 19:47.259
TWO FINE SONS.

19:47.353 --> 19:49.936
MAN, WAR STINKS.

19:53.401 --> 19:54.983
<i>(Sergeant)
LIEUTENANT?</i>

19:59.198 --> 20:01.314
CAPTAIN GUNTHER
WANTS TO SEE YOU.

20:04.995 --> 20:07.703
LIEUTENANT, YOU ARE
TO REPORT BACK TO DIVISION.

20:07.790 --> 20:09.155
BACK TO DIVISION?

20:09.250 --> 20:10.911
YEAH. THEY WANT
TO LOOK YOU OVER.

20:11.001 --> 20:13.163
IT'LL BE A NICE COUPLE
WEEKS REST FOR YOU.

20:13.254 --> 20:14.540
TAKE YOUR GEAR WITH YOU.

20:14.630 --> 20:15.961
OKAY.

20:16.048 --> 20:17.834
THANK YOU, CAPTAIN.

20:36.110 --> 20:37.350
<i>[suspense music]</i>

20:52.001 --> 20:54.163
<i>(soldier)
LIEUTENANT FITZGERALD?</i>

20:54.253 --> 20:56.995
<i>THE JEEP'S READY TO TAKE
YOU BACK TO DIVISION, SIR</i>

20:57.089 --> 20:58.830
ANY TIME
YOU'RE READY.

20:58.924 --> 21:00.585
LIEUTENANT
FITZGERALD?

21:00.676 --> 21:02.542
WHAT?

21:02.636 --> 21:04.013
THIS YOUR BAG, SIR?

21:04.096 --> 21:06.679
YES, THAT'S MY BAG.

21:06.766 --> 21:08.723
MAY I PUT IT IN THE
JEEP FOR YOU, SIR?

21:08.809 --> 21:10.425
THANK YOU VERY MUCH.

21:10.519 --> 21:11.975
WELL, SIR,
WE'RE READY

21:12.062 --> 21:13.314
ANY TIME YOU ARE.

21:20.279 --> 21:21.735
<i>[suspense music]</i>

21:38.923 --> 21:40.459
WELL, IT'S
A LITTLE BOUNCY, SIR

21:40.549 --> 21:42.506
BUT IT SURE
BEATS WALKING.

21:42.593 --> 21:44.550
YOU'RE GOING BACK TO DIVISION?

21:44.637 --> 21:46.173
YEAH.

21:46.263 --> 21:48.300
FURTHER BACK I GET,
THE BETTER I LIKE IT.

21:48.390 --> 21:50.222
YOU'RE TAKING
THE CONVENIENT ROAD?

21:50.309 --> 21:52.767
YEAH. THERE'S A BRIDGE
UP THERE ON THE HIGHWAY.

21:52.853 --> 21:56.062
THE ENGINEERS THINK THEY'VE
SPOTTED SOME MINES UP THE ROAD

21:56.148 --> 21:57.730
THEY HAVEN'T
DUG THEM UP YET

21:57.817 --> 21:59.728
SO STAY CLOSE
TO THE SHOULDERS.

21:59.819 --> 22:01.480
I WANT YOU
TO TAKE GOOD CARE

22:01.570 --> 22:03.186
OF THE
LIEUTENANT HERE.

22:03.280 --> 22:05.487
<i>SERGEANT, I'M THE
MOST CAREFUL DRIVER</i>

22:05.574 --> 22:07.781
<i>IN THE UNITED
STATES ARMY.</i>

22:07.868 --> 22:11.236
IF I CAN LIFT THIS HERE JEEP
AND VVALK TIPPYTOE CARRYING IT

22:11.330 --> 22:13.412
BELIEVE ME, BROTHER,
I'D DO IT.

22:15.751 --> 22:18.493
<i>LIEUTENANT, YOU MAY AS
WELL GET COMFORTABLE.</i>

22:18.587 --> 22:20.498
<i>I GUESS WE GOT ABOUT
A FOUR-HOUR RIDE</i>

22:20.589 --> 22:22.375
<i>AHEAD OF US.</i>

22:26.637 --> 22:29.174
<i>DO WE?</i>

22:29.265 --> 22:32.803
I DOUBT IT.

22:32.893 --> 22:34.600
<i>[suspense music]</i>

22:50.661 --> 22:52.151
<i>[soft harmonica playing]</i>

22:57.751 --> 23:01.164
YOU PLAY THAT
PRETTY GOOD.

23:01.255 --> 23:03.337
ONE HAND.

23:12.308 --> 23:16.677
<i>[loud explosion in distance]</i>

23:18.355 --> 23:19.971
DID YOU HEAR THAT?

23:20.065 --> 23:21.476
THUNDER?

23:21.567 --> 23:22.978
I DON'T THINK SO.

23:23.068 --> 23:24.934
IT SOUNDED MORE LIKE
AN EXPLOSION.

23:25.029 --> 23:26.690
<i>[suspense music]</i>

23:31.201 --> 23:33.283
MAYBE IT WAS THUNDER. YEAH.

23:33.370 --> 23:36.112
THAT'S WHAT IT WAS--
PROBABLY THUNDER.

23:40.377 --> 23:43.620
[plays harmonica]

23:43.714 --> 23:47.252
<i>(male narrator) FROM WILLIAM
SHAKESPEARE, RICHARD THE THIRD,</i>

23:47.343 --> 23:49.960
<i>A SMALL EXCERPT,
THE LINE READS,</i>

23:50.054 --> 23:52.716
<i>"HE HAS COME TO OPEN
THE PURPLE TESTAMENT</i>

23:52.806 --> 23:55.548
<i>OF BLEEDING WAR."</i>

23:55.643 --> 23:58.305
<i>AND FOR LIEUTENANT
WILLIAM FITZGERALD--</i>

23:58.395 --> 24:01.763
<i>"A" COMPANY, FIRST PLATOON,
THE TESTAMENT IS CLOSED.</i>

24:01.857 --> 24:07.273
<i>LIEUTENANT FITZGERALD
HAS FOUND THE TWILIGHT ZONE.</i>

24:12.451 --> 24:15.910
<i>(male presenter, off) ROD SERLING,
THE CREATOR OF TWILIGHT ZONE,</i>

24:15.996 --> 24:18.078
<i>WILL TELL YOU
ABOUT NEXT WEEK'S STORY</i>

24:18.165 --> 24:20.452
<i>AFTER THIS WORD
FROM OUR ALTERNATE SPONSOR</i>

24:20.542 --> 24:23.500
<i>AND NOW, R. SERLING.</i>

24:23.587 --> 24:25.874
NEXT WEEK,
ON THE TWILIGHT ZONE

24:25.965 --> 24:29.424
WE OFFER YOU THE UNBELIEVABLE
ALONG WITH AN EXPLANATION.

24:29.510 --> 24:31.592
THREE MEN VISIT
A STRANGE NEW WORLD

24:31.679 --> 24:33.636
WITH PEOPLE, CARS,
HOUSES, THE WORKS.

24:33.722 --> 24:35.633
BUT SOMETHING'S
WRONG IN THE SCENE.

24:35.724 --> 24:38.136
SOMETHING VERY ABNORMAL
AMIDST THE NORMAL.

24:38.227 --> 24:42.141
YOU'LL SEE VVHAT I MEAN VVHEN NEXT VVEEK
VVE BRING YOU "ELEGY" BY CHARLES BEAUMONT.

24:42.231 --> 24:45.940
IT STARS CECIL KELLAWAY.
THANK YOU AND GOOD NIGHT.

25:28.402 --> 25:32.396
<i>(male presenter, off) KIMBERLY CLARK
INVITES YOU TO WATCH STEVE MCQUEEN</i>

25:32.489 --> 25:34.742
<i>IN</i> WANTED DEAD OR ALIVE.

25:34.825 --> 25:38.159
<i>SATURDAY NIGHTS OVER MOST
OF THESE SAME STATIONS.</i>
